### Schema Access Roles

Each schema will have three database roles:

| Role Pattern | Purpose | Privileges | Inherits From |
|--------------|---------|------------|---------------|
| `SC_R_<schema>` | Read access | SELECT on tables, views, functions | — |
| `SC_W_<schema>` | Write access | INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, EXECUTE, streams, tasks | SC_R |
| `SC_C_<schema>` | Create access | CREATE TABLE, VIEW, PROCEDURE, etc. | SC_W |

### Role Hierarchy

Schema roles connect to database roles, which connect to account functional roles:

```
Account Role    Database Role    Schema Roles
─────────────   ─────────────    ─────────────
{%- for zone in zone_list %}
{%- for schema in schema_definitions if schema.zone == zone %}
DP_READ      →    DB_R     ←    SC_R_{{ schema.schema_name | upper }}
DP_WRITE     →    DB_W     ←    SC_W_{{ schema.schema_name | upper }}
DP_ADMIN     →    DB_C     ←    SC_C_{{ schema.schema_name | upper }}
{%- endfor %}
{%- endfor %}
```

### Schema Settings

| Setting | Value |
|---------|-------|
| **Managed Access** | Yes (WITH MANAGED ACCESS) |
| **Data Retention** | Inherited from database |
| **Initial Owner** | SYSADMIN |
| **Final Owner** | Data Product Owner (after Role & Access Control) |

